FT  11 MAY 92 / International Company News: US broker fined Dollars 36m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHARLESTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MORGAN STANLEY, the US broker, was fined Dollars 36m on charges by the state
of West Virginia that it was responsible for trades that lost millions of
dollars from the state's investment fund in 1987, Reuter reports from
Charleston.
A spokeswoman for the firm said it planned to appeal. 'We expect it to be
overturned on appeal,' she said.
West Virginia sued Morgan Stanley over about Dollars 40m lost in three deals
in which the firm was involved in 1987. Judge Andrew MacQueen had ruled it
owed the state Dollars 32m from those trades, leaving the jury to rule on
whether Morgan Stanley was guilty of fraud.
The spokeswoman said the West Virginia Consolidated Fund, involved in the
transactions, realised gains of more than Dollars 500m during the period in
question, even as it was losing the Dollars 32m.
Judge MacQueen had ruled before the trial opened that those trades violated
the Consolidated Fund's guidelines.
