<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The makers of Channel 4's six-part series Female Parts (9.00) are clearly
hoping to hook a huge audience by starting with the most provocative of the
series: 'Rude Women'. This, we are assured, is 'a full frontal assault on
the myth that women don't like sex, don't talk about it and never make the
first move', which sounds like a trio of straw, er, women which should not
take too much knocking down. The Pussy Posse hold a safe sex party, the
editor of one of the new spate of women's sex magazines explains just what
you cannot show, and Susanna, who has a drawer full of chains, explains how
she has never found any man tough enough to tie her up.
Horizon looks into the question of who really discovered the virus that
causes Aids. In 1984 American Robert Gallo claimed the credit, but today
most of those involved accept that the discovery rightfully belongs to Dr
Luc Montagnier of the Pasteur Institute in Paris (8.10 BBC2).
In Panorama the FT's John Plender tries to establish whether, in future,
owning a house in Britain will still be a sure way of doubling your money
(9.30 BBC1).
