<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 92 / Dispute looms on union merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE newly formed Amalgamated Engineering and Electrical Union may become the
focus of a Trades Union Congress row over the recruitment of a non-TUC
breakaway group of airline cabin staff.
The row may jeopardise the readmittance to the TUC of the electricians'
section of the new union, formed by the amalgamation of the EETPU
electricians' and the AEU engineering unions. The EETPU was expelled by the
TUC in 1988.
The electricians' section has disclosed that, over the past few days, it has
agreed to provide services 'on an agency basis in the first stage' to Cabin
Crew '89. The 5,000-strong cabin crew group broke away from the TGWU general
union in 1989.
Initially - and controversially - Cabin Crew '89 was given financial support
by Balpa, the airline officers' association.
Cabin Crew '89, which consists mainly of British Airways staff, has now
severed its links with Balpa and has turned to the white-collar section of
the electricians' grouping within the AEEU. The electricians will provide
support services at first.
The EETPU section of the AEEU said yesterday that the arrangement had 'not
been entered into to be provocative or controversial' but was between 'one
non-TUC-affiliated trade union and another non-TUC-affiliated union'.
</TEXT>
