<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAY 92 / Groups accused on abuses of rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO THIRDS of the UK's top companies have links with countries that are
abusers of human rights, according to a report published today, Scheherazade
Daneshkhu writes.
The Ethical Investment Research Service (Eiris) which screens companies for
private investors to see whether they meet certain ethical criteria, says
that 36 of the 50 largest UK companies are involved.
'Many UK company groups have subsidiary and associated companies all over
the world,' Eiris says. 'By operating in a country, the company group is
making a direct investment in that country's economy.'
The survey covers all 590 companies in the FTA All-Share Index at the end of
last year. It found that 200 had subsidiary or associated companies in one
or more of the countries identified, while 31 companies had significant
subsidiaries in countries with high levels of human rights abuses.
They included Thorn-EMI, the electronics group, which employs 340 people in
a subsidiary in Mexico, a country from which Amnesty International has
received reports of torture. The report also cites Tate and Lyle which has
subsidiaries or associated companies in Kenya, Somalia, South Africa, Sri
Lanka and Sudan, all of which suffer human rights abuses.
The top 50 companies by market value which are not identified by the
oppressive-regime criteria used by Eiris are: Abbey National, Argyll Group,
Associated British Foods, BAA, British Gas, Eurotunnel, Kingfisher, Land
Securities, Marks and Spencer, National Power, Reuters Holdings, J.
Sainsbury, Tesco and Vodafone Group.
Oppressive Regimes. Eiris, Freepost, London SW8 1BR. Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
