<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 92 / Getting up from the canvas: A recovery in the market for
contemporary art
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Christie's sale of contemporary art in New York on Tuesday evening was a
tense affair. The market had been in free fall for almost three years. The
value of even major works by well respected artists had virtually halved.
Yet Christie's was offering an important composition by Andy Warhol, '210
Coca-Cola Bottles', a painting depicting seven rows of bottles stencilled on
to a silkscreen, with a hefty estimate of up to Dollars 2.8m.
Warhol's prices have fluctuated markedly since his death in 1987. And
although its early date, 1962, made the work important, the general feeling
was that Christie's, and the vendor, Martin Blinder, whose recession-hit
company sells art in shopping malls, had over-reached themselves.
In the event, bidding was brisk, with four potential buyers. The work was
finally sold to the Zurich dealer Thomas Ammann for Dollars 2m, well below
estimates but still a weighty price for Warhol, whose long-term reputation
is far from established. Christie's gamble had paid off and the market for
contemporary art, the most fickle sector of the arts trade, had given clear
signs of recovery.
'I am more than fairly pleased,' said Christie's expert Diane Upright after
the New York sale. Along with her rival Lucy Mitchell-Innes at Sotheby's she
had succeeded during the week in re-establishing a solidly based market in
contemporary art.
Prices may be considerably reduced on 1990 levels but at least there were
buyers, mainly American and European private collectors, for the select lots
which had been allowed to appear at the rostrum.
By concentrating on paintings that had not been on offer for many years,
that were in good condition and carrying low reserves, Christie's managed to
sell 82 per cent by value of its 67 lots for a total of Dollars 11.26m.
Sotheby's received Dollars 12.3m from 56 lots, and sold 76 per cent of its
works.
Both salerooms were lucky as well as bold. They each had an important seller
keen to dispose of desirable paintings at low prices. Sotheby's were
marketing a series of works owned by Charles Saatchi, co-founder of Saatchi
&amp; Saatchi, the advertising group, and the dominant force in the contemporary
art market for over a decade. He is currently jettisoning important works by
artists he helped to popularise in the early 1980s so as to acquire the art
of a later generation as well as the occasional modern masterpiece. Saatchi
can afford to accept low prices since he bought the works for very modest
sums.
His imprimatur ensured that 'Bob's World', an early 'plate' composition (in
which broken plates are stuck to the canvas to create a greater physical
impact) by the controversial Julian Schnabel, sold for Dollars 319,000.
Other Saatchi paintings to sell included one of Cy Twombly's many 'Untitled'
canvases, bought by Saatchi's dealer Larry Gagosian for Dollars 1.65m, and
Dollars 627,000 for a pastiche of the Old Master Vermeer by the British
artist Malcolm Morley.
This was an auction record for Morley and underlined the growing
internationalism in the market for contemporary art. Traditionally,
Americans bought the abstract expressionism of the post-war New York
artists; Germans the work of their painters like Baselitz, Kiefer, and
Richter; and the French stuck with the Paris School. Now artists can cross
borders much more easily. Significantly, this week's sales brought the first
purchases from Taiwan, although the Japanese dealers, who entered this
market at its 1989 peak, were conspicuously absent.
Christie's sale centred on the works of Frederik Roos, the Swedish financier
who established his collection during the 1980's and who bought widely from
artists of various nationalities.
Roos died last year, aged 40 and loaded with debt, and Christie's has the
challenge of disposing of his collection. It has the advantage of
negotiating with a deceased estate, which helped it force low estimates and
reserves on the art. But even so, Christie's was amazed at its success in
marketing 188 of the best Roos acquisitions.
Virtually all were sold, for a total of Dollars 7.8m. Work by English
sculptors patronised by Roos, such as Tony Cragg and Barry Flanagan, sold
for auction record prices - Dollars 99,000 for a Cragg composition of three
giant bronze canisters, and Dollars 93,500 for a Flanagan bronze of one hare
balancing another on its nose.
Internationalism is not completely established - Sotheby's failed to sell
Saatchi's important nude portrait by Lucian Freud, 'Night Interior',
probably because the estimate of Dollars 500,000 was excessive for an artist
not well known in the US - but it is the best hope for the market's future.
For contemporary art still faces problems. There was very little buying this
week by dealers, who are sitting on enormous bank overdrafts in unvisited
galleries with vaults full of over-priced pictures.
And the main reason that the auctions were successful was that Sotheby's and
Christie's had fixed reserves even lower than those at last November's
auctions.
The market is in convalescence and is still far from buoyant. It was
noticeable that neither owners nor auction houses were willing to risk the
great icons of modern art - works by Jasper Johns or Jackson Pollock, de
Kooning or Lichtenstein, were not on offer this week.
Diane Upright reckons that the top price that anyone is currently prepared
to pay for a painting by a modern master is Dollars 10m. Three years ago a
de Kooning, 'Interchange', sold for Dollars 20.678m to a Japanese buyer and
a Jasper Johns, 'False Start', changed hands for Dollars 17m.
As the international economy moves out of recession, dealers and collectors
expect that the contemporary art market should continue to recover from its
sickbed. In any event, it will not lose its ability to shock.
The artist in keenest demand, whose prices have continued to rise during the
recession, is Robert Gober. His speciality is making creations of urinals,
beds, and, in particular, kitchen sinks. One of his beds, composed of
enamel, wood, cotton and wool, soared above its estimate on Tuesday to make
a record Dollars 180,000 - but also to create new doubts about the aesthetic
value of contemporary art.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
