<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 92 / Dewhurst to shed up to 1,500 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEWHURST, which runs the UK's biggest chain of butchers shops, confirmed
yesterday that it is to close up to 600 of its 1,006 high-street outlets in
the next 18 months, with the loss of up to 1,500 jobs.
Dewhurst is a subsidiary of Union International, which handles the food
businesses of privately-owned Vestey.
The Vestey group was recently forced to make substantial provisions on its
property portfolio, and some observers regard the decision to slim the
Dewhurst chain as partly a response to that. Union International and Vestey
declined to comment yesterday.
Mr Mike Carter, marketing manager of Dewhurst, said the company planned to
sell some of the shops as going concerns and that others would be taken over
by current managers.
Mr Carter was unable to put a market value on the sale. He added that
Dewhurst would review the situation during the next 18 months and, should
business recover, the company might dispose of fewer than the planned 600
units.
The company has no plans to introduce franchise arrangements for the shops
involved, and does not intend to close en bloc in any particular part of the
UK.
Dewhurst has been hit by factors including the spread of Sunday trading, the
growing strength of large supermarket chains and the recession. According to
Verdict, a retail research company, the large grocery chains now account for
more than half of all carcass meat and 92 per cent of all bacon, ham,
poultry and meat products sold in the UK.
Mr Carter denied that a growing tendency towards vegetarianism had reduced
Dewhurst's market.
</TEXT>
