<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 92 / BT plans to reward its smooth operators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BT STAFF who whistle while they work could find themselves the proud
recipients of a Pierre Cardin simulated pearl necklace or a Sony Walkman,
under a management scheme to lift the workforce's low spirits.
The scheme is being introduced as BT cuts 24,000 jobs.
Managers who feel a particular employee is 'living BT's values' will be able
to nominate the individual for a gift to be chosen from a catalogue of 50
items.
The Union of Communication Workers, which represents BT telephone operators,
reacted angrily. 'This is yet another cynical attempt to manipulate the
workforce,' said Ms Janice Stone, a UCW national official.
Operators have been particularly badly hit by the job cuts. A recent
internal survey found that 44 per cent of the 216,000-strong workforce were
afraid of losing their jobs. Only a third of those who took part in the
survey were proud of the company.
BT, which says it expects to award thousands of the gifts, claims the scheme
is a first as it is not an incentive scheme but a reward to staff who
implement company values.
As an illustration, BT says an installation engineer who alerted a customer
to a 'hitherto undiscovered problem with their telephone' and whistled while
he fixed it might be eligible for an award if a customer wrote in to say
what a 'marvellous advertisement' he was for BT.
The UCW is sceptical about how motivated staff will be by the gifts: 'It may
be a forlorn hope for BT that giving away trinkets can turn this appalling
loss of morale around. Pictures in the brochures of smiling workers
applauding a colleague being thanked by a manager are hardly likely to ring
many bells with UCW members at BT.'
National Grid plan, Page 3
</TEXT>
