<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 92 / Arts: Back to the classics - Radio
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By B. A. YOUNG
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CLASSIC Serials on Radio 4, on Saturday evening, repeated on Friday
afternoons, are the very thing for those who know the names of all the great
English novels but either read them too long since or have not read them at
all. I don't know when I read Smollett's The Expedition of Humphry Clinker,
but it is so full of incident I certainly could not remember half of it.
Scott Cherry's adaptation, extracting the events from the letters Smollett
presents them in, is packed with amusing narrative detail. The first
instalment on Saturday mostly covered Matthew Bramble's journey from
Brambleton to Bristol, Bramble being the splendid Timothy West. In his party
are his sister Tabitha, his nephew Jery, his niece Lydia, his doctor, Lewis,
the servant Winifred.
Love is frustrated whenever it appears - Tabitha's for Lewis, Lydia's for
the actor Wilson, whom Jery challenges to a duel but succeeds only in
killing a cow. Transient affairs like Jervis's death after climbing a
staircase to deliver a letter are done as importantly as the major things.
And Humphry Clinker? He is the ragged postilion the party meets on its
arrival in Bath at the very end of this first hour, in which there wasn't a
dull moment. Clive Brill was the director.
Radio 3's Drama Now on Tuesday, The Cello and the Nightingale, was less a
drama than a dramatic imitation of a feature. Patricia Cleveland-Peck wrote
it to mark the centenary of cellist Beatrice Harrison, and to recall her
fascinating achievement in making the BBC broadcast the nightingales singing
in her Surrey garden while she played the cello.
She had trouble in getting the Company (as it was then) to try anything so
improbable, even with sundry telephone calls direct to Mr Reith. When at
last all was agreed, the necessary kit spread all over the garden, a mike
next to the nightingales' nest, she also had trouble in getting the birds to
sing. She sat playing favourite items for a couple of hours - then, just as
the BBC was ready to pack up, they began. The broadcast was a tremendous
success, and was done again every year for 12 years.
Ms Cleveland-Peck had her troubles too, for the truth is that, for those of
us not involved, that evening was tedious. Reminiscences of Beatrice
Harrison's life, soliloquies of her thoughts as she played, touches of 1924
wireless, did not make it seem less so. Diana Quick was charming as Miss
Harrison, and Julian Lloyd Webber played Elgar, Delius, Dvorak and the
Londonderry Air.
What would Smollett have made of Radio 5's Open Mike on Monday, a six-part
piece by Shaun Prendergast about life in a local independent radio station,
Valley Sound? I reckon anyone as good on significant detail as Smollett
would certainly have cared about such things. Mike (Gary Love) is the
undisciplined guy who thinks the material they put out must attract
attention even if it's risky. He has got one of the girl reporters pregnant
and is virtually under three weeks' notice (though not for that). I could
not follow everything, because the voices (young, eager) are so much alike;
and at least so far there seems too little discipline in the station. But
I'll be back.
I heard the second of Radio 1's current social programmes, Tell it like it
is, to learn what new problem would be exhibited. There was miserable talk
of jealousy, poverty, bullying and sexual abuse, particularly of girls by
their mothers - not a common subject of discussion. How typical can all this
be of our society? And how are such wretched people persuaded to talk, not
to Samaritans, but to recording engineers condensing their wretchedness for,
as we must concur, public benefit?
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-9041</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEIBCACYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 92 / Arts: Why artists were drawn to Dieppe - William Packer
reviews the Brighton Festival's principle exhibition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM PACKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRIGHTON Festival, feeling itself perceived as principally a festival of
music, has this year given its programme of exhibitions a particular
emphasis. Rendez-vous a Dieppe is its principal offering, a celebration, as
its sub-title puts it, of the town and its artists from Turner to Braque.
Admirably put together by John Willet, an English art-historian who lives
just outside Dieppe, it indeed answers that deceptively simple brief, and
the essentially uncurious visitor may pass happily down that chronology,
indulged at each point by particular yet often unfamiliar examples of the
highest quality.
Its true substance is quite as much in social as art-historical, its subject
the strong link established over more than a century, by way of Newhaven,
between the two opposing and yet so very different popular watering-places
that face each other across the Channel. But important though Brighton has
long remained to the English, as an occasional resort - raffish, bracing,
above all accessible - it has never drawn to it a community of artists.
Individuals may have come and gone, but there was never a group, a Brighton
school, an artists' colony. The serious creative traffic was always passing
through, and for the most part one way.
Quite why one town should become a hive and focus of creative energy and
another not is always an open question. It is not simply by a quality of the
picturesque, for both France and England have quaint and historic towns, all
still quite artist-free in any proper art-historical sense. The artist may
well stop for a while en route, but soon passes on, a few studies made,
perhaps, a canvas filled, but nothing more and never again. It takes a
Venice or a Paris to establish the interest permanently. Where a collective
habit does form, such election seems always arbitrary and temporary, a
creature of chance and circumstance.
Dieppe was always a special case, but even Dieppe's moment has come and
gone, with few easels now among the tourists. For the French painters at a
certain time, the harbours, cliffs and wide skies of the western Normandy
coast were obviously attractive, but no more so than anywhere else within
easy reach of Paris. The Seine valley soon drew Monet to the sea, for
example, and Braque came to live a little along the coast at Varengeville;
but even so, for the Frenchman, there was always the South.
For the English, however, France is the South, and Dieppe the first town of
the South and the great escape. For so many of us simply to be in France is
enough. In days of slower travel the temptation to draw breath after the
crossing, to stay a day or two and look around, was even stronger than it is
now. An artist might take a house and studio perhaps, find himself staying
longer than ever he planned, show his work to others who might well come
over and take a house - and stay rather longer than planned . . .
It is thus hardly remarkable that of the artists associated with Dieppe,
rather more are English than French, nor that of the French, some such as
Helleu and Blanche, should have had close English connections. Most
particular of all, it was Sickert who came and stayed, and by virtue of his
commanding authority among them, persuaded so many of his fellows and
disciples to follow him. In earlier years, such painters as Turner and
Bonington came over and passed through: between the wars, Ben Nicholson and
Christopher Wood came over to sit at the feet of Braque: but of them all,
the Sickert battalions at the turn of the century were those who made Dieppe
most their own.
Here they all are, the Camden Townites, Gilman, Ginner and Spencer Gore, the
fin-de siecle aesthetes, Conder and Beardsley, Ben's father William
Nicholson who is at the very least as significant a painter as his son, and
William Rothenstein, and Whistler, and Fergusson, and Matthew Smith. From
Delacroix and Daubigny to Monet and Pissarro to Braque and Gauguin, the
French are properly celebrated, but this remains, by its very nature and
emphasis, a gratifyingly English exhibition.
'Rendez-vous a Dieppe': Brighton Museum &amp; Art Gallery, until June 30;
sponsored by Sealink Newhaven-Dieppe
</TEXT>
