<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 92 / Arts: Falstaff grows in stature - Malcolm Rutherford reviews
Henry IV and other London openings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM RUTHERFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ADRIAN Noble's production of King Henry IV Part 2 has arrived at the
Barbican and, like Part I, is even better than when it was first performed
at Stratford a year ago. The triumph lies not only in the synthesis of the
two parts, but in the way that that Part 2 has elements not touched upon in
Part I. The most obvious is the move to the countryside. Aside from the
battle scenes, Part I is mainly about life in and around London. Where the
action ranges wider, it is to the outlying areas: Wales and Northumberland.
They are full of wild men like Glendower and Hotspur.
Part 2 moves into the civilised English countryside of Gloucestershire.
Instead of warriors it is full of slow-witted lawyers like the Justices,
Shallow and Silence; instead of tribal passions inspiring the troops, there
are reluctant conscripts like Francis Feeble and Ralph Mouldy. What we see
in Part 2 is the beginning of English nationalism. The next wars will not be
the southern English resisting the north, but all the English fighting the
French.
The Gloucestershire scenes in Noble's production are outstanding because
they show the provincial deference to the capital. To Justice Shallow,
Falstaff is not the disreputable, unreliable fellow he seems in London: he
is to be looked up to because he has stayed at the centre and been knighted.
In Gloucestershire, Robert Stephens's Falstaff looks like a man of
authority. He moves about the southern counties recruiting soldiers. He may
even drink less than Shallow; at least he holds it better. That is not how
he is seen in London.
The performances by David Bradley and Anthony Douse as Shallow and Silence
respectively are impeccable, as is that by Christopher Luscombe in the even
smaller part of Davy, Shallow's servant. How, you can see Falstaff
wondering, is it possible to get such a good valet in a land of yokels?
Other indelible scenes are first the illness, then the death of Julian
GLover's Henry IV. As the dying man's memories of a lifetime come back, he
recalls that there was less than 10 years between the deposition of Richard
II and now his own passing away. In the meantime, a nation has has
developed, or so Shakespeare would have us believe.
*****
One of the reasons why Ariel Dorfman's Death and the Maiden is such a good
play is its ambiguity: in the transition from dictatorship to democracy
nobody is quite sure who did what under the old regime and how much of the
past should be investigated. As a play, Karate Billy Comes Home at the Royal
Court's Theatre Upstairs, which is where The Maiden also began, is not in
the same league, but it is broadly the same genre. Just as betrayals ran
deep in Pinochet's Chile, in the old East Germany practically everyone spied
on everyone else. Too much is known about the recriminations now going on to
doubt the basic authenticity of Klaus Pohl's piece, even if the plot is
excessively melodramatic.
Billy was a prospective Olympic multi-gold medallist, having already swept
the board at the world student games in Bratislava. As such, he was a jewel
in the crown of the East German state, but was also being wooed to defect to
the US. The East Germans tampered with him medically in order to keep him at
home: he spent 13 years in an asylum developing some of the attributes of a
monkey man.
When the Berlin Wall came down he was released. Most of the play is about
who was responsible for for betraying him. Even the local pastor turns out
to have been an informer and Billy's devoted sister was not entirely
innocent. The piece contains an extraordinary scene where the sister
declares her incestuous love for her brother; it is not unmoving, but of
dubious relevance to the plot. In the background is a man from the Deutsche
Bank who has come to mop up the remains of the East German economy. He
learns that it is helpful to know how the informer system worked under the
old regime, for the old habits clearly die hard.
The play has its flaws, but strikes me as a more interesting work than
Howard Brenton's Berlin Bertie at the Royal Court's main house. It
concentrates on East Germany as it is and avoids spurious comparisons
between eastern and western decadence. Billy, wild-haired, wild-eyed and
full of animal strength, is superbly played by Kevin McMonagie. The
translation by David Tushingham; the direction by Stephen Unwin has moments
of genuine tension.
*****
It is hard not to like As You Like It. The most pastoral of Shakespeare's
plays, it has scarcely a touch of malice. Nevertheless, James Robert
Carson's production at Greenwich makes heavy going of it. The opening is
funereal and the eary scenes are stultified by over-formal costumes and a
peculiar Grecian frieze. When the scene changes to picnicland in the Forest
of Arden, however, the production perks up Philip Franks as Jacques performs
the remarkable feat of speaking the seven ages of man lines as if they had
just been written. He shines again when he makes his dignified, melancholy
departure at the end. There is nothing camp about Jemma Redgrave's Rosalind.
She hardly even looks as if she is dressed as a boy. Instead she is an
intelligent youth who has fallen madly in love and enjoying every minute of
it. This is a very youthful production which gets more exuberant as it goes
on. The cast includes a wonderful Welsh Phebe, Buddug Morgan.
*****
Viktor Slavkin's Cerceau, subtitled 'I'm Forty But I Don't Look It', is
playing for the first time in English at the Orange Tree in Richmond.
Written in 1983, its chief interest is in the way it foreshadowed glasnost
in the period just before President Gorbachev. The characters, gathered in
an inherited, but dilapidated country house outside Moscow, do not speak as
if they are wholly oppressed by the regime, but neither are they part of it.
They seem to be waiting for something to happen: these were, after all, the
years of stagnation in the Soviet Union. The debt to Chekhov and The Cherry
Orchard, written shortly before the revolution, is openly acknowledged by
Slavkin. Nothing much does happen: the guests at the house discover cerceau,
an old aristocratic game played with quoits on summer lawns and an old man
turns up who remembers pre-1917 Russia. The piece is lovingly translated and
directed by Adrian Brine and it certainly catches an atmosphere of ennui.
Henry IV, Part 2 in repertory at the Barbican (071) 638 8891. Karate Billy,
Royal Court Upstairs (071) 730 1745. As You Like It, Greenwich Theatre (081)
858 7755, Cerceau, Orange Tree, Richmond (081) 940 3633
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
