<PROFILE>_AN-CEIBCACWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 92 / Arts: Odets in Ayckbournsville
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALASTAIR MACAULAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'THE TIME is 1938 and the place is a dentist's waiting room in a New York
office building.' In 1938, the year Clifford Odets wrote Rocket to the Moon,
he appeared on the cover of Time Magazine. He was 32, and the Broadway plays
he had already written included Waiting for Lefty, Awake and Sing, Paradise
Lost and Golden Boy. His kind of realism had an intense and immediate
influence on Elia Kazan, Arthur Miller and others. How interesting today, as
his works are becoming period pieces, to see Rocket to the Moon in
Scarborough - in Alan Ayckbournsville.
For one thing, this is less of a period piece than you might expect. Its
theme is perennial. Husband (dentist Ben Stark), almost 40 and henpecked by
wife (Belle), falls in love with secretary (Cleo). Secretary, almost 20,
falls in love with him. He feels he has never been so alive, she finds him
more appealing than any other man, but he cannot bring himself to leave his
wife.
For another, Malcolm Hebden has directed the play handsomely. Sarah-Jane
Fenton, playing Cleo as a Marilyn Monroe of 1938, is first-rate, always
quietly writhing in her tight uniform, perfectly catching the girl's accent
helplessly exploiting her teeth and eyes. Only Kenneth Price, as Ben, is too
weak; he lacks the part's mixture of neurosis and integrity.
Odets spices the story with humour and, thank heaven, with incidental
detail. Afterwards, you also remember gratefully the shrewd medico
neighbour, Frenchy Jensen (excellently played by Dale Ripley), the always
surprising father-in-law Mr Prince (James Tomlinson) and the fact that the
secretary Cleo has a gold-digger streak, lies about her background and is
fairly dumb. In an immortal line, she tells Ben 'You know something? I can't
read Shakespeare. The print's too small.'
The play has two big flaws. It is bogged down - as Arthur Miller's plays
have been too - by the leadenness of its philosophising and symbolism.
Characters keep reminding each other that this particular situation is
actually 'like millions of others.' Frenchy no sooner touches on the subject
of this love than he has to rhapsodise cynically about all Love. And the
sheer dramaturgy of Rocket is creaky. Ben seems to be a dentist virtually
without patients. But then, how could he have time for them? Even at 10 pm
his friends and acquaintances are busily popping in and out of his
waiting-room and catching each other in mid-revelation as if this were
Feydeau's A Flea in her Ear.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
