<DOCNO>FT922-9096</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEIBCABFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920509
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 92 / The Lex Column: Germany
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Germany's public sector pay round has been such a humiliation for the
government that it is easy to overdo its implications for the markets. The
actual settlement will prove more expensive for the employers than the
arbitration deal they originally rejected, so they could have saved
themselves the trouble of a strike. Yet the final percentage is still within
the range of expectations pencilled in by most economists. It should not of
itself upset the Bundesbank.
A more pressing problem remains the explosion in German money supply. If
April's figure, due in a couple of weeks, does show an annual growth of over
10 per cent, as many economists fear, the central bank may come under strong
pressure to raise rates again. Though interest rates are a blunt weapon,
there are not many alternatives: rationing Lombard facility advances to the
banking system would raise money market rates anyway.
The bond market looks likely to suffer whatever happens. Premature easing by
the Bundesbank would add to market worries about a government which, in the
aftermath of the strike, appears to have lost its grip. If interest rates
are maintained or increased, the steep inversion of the yield curve will
continue to push investor funds towards short-term deposits. The fact that
this is not the case in the UK and France is one more reason to expect
spreads between government bonds in these countries and Germany to narrow
further. But despite sterling's astonishing performance against the D-Mark
since Tuesday's UK rate cut, it would not do to anticipate gilt yields
actually falling below those on German bunds.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 22
</PAGE>
