<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAY 92 / Foreign Exchanges: Dollar stages good recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR strengthened against the D-Mark yesterday after better than
forecast US employment figures indicated an upturn in the US economy in
April, writes James Blitz.
The market reacted optimistically to the non-farm payroll figures for April,
which showed a rise in employment of 126,000. As a result the dollar ended
up over a pfennig against the D-Mark, closing at DM1.6475 after a previous
close of DM1.6360.
However, analysts thought the jobs figures were not good enough to alter the
market belief that the US recovery is still rather dormant. Fears that the
US Federal Reserve might cut the Fed funds rate again are certain to
resurface next week. 'We can't rule out a further reduction in interest
rates, especially if next week's US retail sales figures come in on the weak
side,' said Mr Neil MacKinnon, chief economist of Yamaichi International in
London. That indicator, which the markets will watch out for closely on
Wednesday, showed only a 0.1 per cent monthly rise in March.
Sterling was, once again, among the most actively traded currencies of the
day, ending up half a pfennig against the D-Mark at DM2.9450. It is now
fifth from bottom of the EMS grid, having overtaken the Italian, French and
Danish currencies this week.
There were no new factors boosting the British currency yesterday, beyond
investor confidence in the one European country certain to have stable
government for the next five years. According to Mr Jim O'Neill, head of
research at Swiss Banking Corporation in London, the outlook for sterling
remains strong, with every possibility that it could soon test DM2.97.
'Sterling has been one of the most volatile currencies this year,' he said,
'with plenty of potential for profit and loss there.'
The D-Mark, by contrast, failed to gain from news that the damaging public
sector strike in Germany had finally ended, and lost out to most currencies
yesterday. The market seemed more concerned that the government had caved in
to the trade unions' demands, raising fears of inflation.
Like sterling, the French franc continued its week-long assault on the
German currency, with the D-mark ending at around FFr3.3630, compared to a
previous close of FFr3.3669.
Yen trading was, once again, very subdued yesterday. But the currency gave
up some of its recent gains after the Japanese Ministry of Finance said it
had no plans for injecting a new fiscal stimulus. This has raised fears that
the Japanese economy is being subjected to policy overkill, and the yen
closed down against the dollar at Y133.35 compared to Y132.70.
</TEXT>
