<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow declines ahead of
employment data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
A LETHARGIC day on Wall Street saw US equities edge lower in quiet trading
ahead of today's release of employment figures for April, writes Karen Zagor
in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average declined 6.04 to 3,363.37 amid slim New
York SE volume of 169m shares. Losing issues narrowly led those advancing by
822 to 812. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 eased 0.93 to 415.86 and the Nasdaq
composite of over-the-counter stocks slipped 2.20 to 587.16.
The market shrugged off the release of jobless claims for the week ended
April 25, which rose 11,000 to 415,000, and turned its attention to today's
unveiling of employment data for April. The Federal Reserve's monetary
policy decisions are often based partly on the employment numbers, and there
has been widespread speculation that the Fed may ease if the numbers are
weaker than expected.
After two days of solid advances, the transportation sector lost ground,
with the Dow Jones Transportation Average finishing off 12.71 at 1,394.99.
AMR, parent of American Airlines, dipped Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 68 5/8 ,
UAL, parent of United Airlines, relinquished Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 125
and USAir edged down Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 14 5/8 .
The release of same-store sales for April by a number of big US retailers
spurred active trading in the sector. Sears was one of the most heavily
traded board issues, falling Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 42 on the back of a
2.1 per cent dip in comparable domestic store sales for the four weeks to
May 2.
Trading was also heavy in Gap Inc, which climbed Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 42
1/4 after reporting a 13 per cent improvement in comparable store sales for
April.
Federal Express dropped Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 40 3/4 . The company is
cutting prices for large-volume customers in a move aimed at improving its
competitiveness.
In over-the-counter trading, FHP International added Dollars  7/8 at Dollars
15 1/4 after the health maintenance organisation services company posted
third-quarter earnings of 45 cents a share, against 36 cents a year ago.
Ben &amp; Jerry 'A' shares jumped Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 41 1/4 after the ice
cream maker announced first-quarter net earnings of 40 cents a share,
compared with 19 cents a year earlier.
Canada
GAINS IN oil and gas shares countered losses in communication issues,
keeping the broad market in Toronto looking unchanged on the day.
The composite index was up just 1.6 at the finish at 3,362.9, while falls
exceeded rises by 273 to 249. Light trading volume of 21.7m shares was well
below Wednesday's 30.5m.
GW Utilities and Gulf Canada Resources said they will jointly try to sell
their controlling interest in Home Oil. The two had been attempting to sell
their interests in Home separately. GW held at CDollars 7 1/4 , Gulf Canada
lost CDollars  1/4 to CDollars 8 1/8 and Home Oil was CDollars  1/4 firmer
at CDollars 16 3/8 .
Magna International 'A' climbed CDollars 2 1/4 to CDollars 32 7/8 , after
gaining CDollars  3/4 the previous day. Market sources said the rise is due
to a recommendation by a Wertheim Schroder analyst.
</TEXT>
