<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / Money Markets: Interest rates softer
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
INTEREST rates in the sterling money markets softened yesterday as the
pound's performance improved on the foreign exchanges.
Sterling's rise to DM2.9400 in the same week that the Bank of England had
signalled a base rate cut of  1/2 percentage point renewed traders'
confidence in the possibility that rates may be shaved again in the
not-too-distant future.
At the same time, the German Bundesbank's decision not to raise its Lombard
rate for emergency funding at its central council meeting yesterday removed
lingering fears that Tuesday's cut in sterling base rate would be
short-lived.
The trade in sterling futures registered greater confidence over the outlook
for rates. The June short sterling contract ended at 89.96, just below its
high for the day, after a previous close of 89.93. That new level implies
that the market believes interest rates in June will be around 10.04 per
cent.
In the interbank market, interest rates edged slightly lower. The rate for
3-month money, seen as an important indicator of future movements, was at 10
1/8 - 1/16 per cent, down from Wednesday's 10 3/16 .
In the discount market, trading was, in the words of one analyst, 'typically
Thursdayish', as traders held back paper in the hope of getting better rates
on Friday, before the weekend. Discount bankers refrained from selling bills
in the morning, even though the Bank of England forecast a large shortage of
around Pounds 1.4bn.
The Bank purchased Pounds 12m of Band-1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent, Pounds
8m of Band-3 bills at 9- 21/32 per cent, and Pounds 13m of Band-4 bills at 9
5/8 - 19/32 per cent. Later, it purchased bills totalling Pounds 1.8bn, made
up of Pounds 3m of Band-3 treasury bills at 9 21/32 per cent, Pounds 136m of
Band-3 bank bills at 9 21/32 per cent, Pounds 3m of Band-4 Treasury bills at
9 19/32 per cent, and Pounds 38m of Band-4 bank bills at 9 19/32 per cent.
In the afternoon, the Bank purchased Pounds 119m of Band-1 Treasury bills at
9 7/8 per cent, Pounds 434m of Band-1 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent, Pounds
337m of Band-2 bank bills at 9 7/8 per cent, Pounds 37m of Band-3 bank bills
at 9 21/32 per cent, and Pounds 25m of Band-4 bank bills at 9 19/32 per
cent. The Bank provided late assistance of around Pounds 285m.
As a result of slack trading in the morning, the overnight rate touched 10
3/4 - 1/2 per cent at one stage, and ended at 9 3/4 - 5/8 per cent.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
