FT  08 MAY 92 / International Company News: Matuschka sells its Frankfurt
currency arm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MATUSCHKA, the Munich-based financial services outfit run by Count
Matuschka, continued its slimming-down exercise yesterday with the sale of
its Frankfurt-based currency managing unit.
The sale, to the business's managers and to Oechsle International Advisers,
a Boston-based international fund management group, follows a series of
disposals during the course of the past year.
In June last year, Mr Manfred Meier-Preschany, a Frankfurt-based corporate
doctor, was brought in to deal with the after-effects of over-expansion in
the late-1980s.
He recommended that the group pull out of currency trading, venture capital,
property consultancy and other peripheral activities.
Mr Meier-Preschany left at the beginning of the year and Count Matuschka
re-assumed the job of chief executive. He has continued the rationalisation
process. In recent months he has sold Matuschka-Capital, Matuschka &amp; Co,
Zurich, and its stake in Techno Venture Management  - all venture capital
operations.
The Count bought out his partners, took his personal stake in the group up
to 66 per cent and restructured the core businesses in a complex transaction
involving EffectInvest, an Austrian private bank.
Matuschka was once spoken of as one of Germany's leading independent
financial services businesses and at its high-point employed more than 468
people. This is down to less than 100 people, although the irrepressible
Count boasts of the group's strong balance sheet and has plans to expand the
core businesses.
</TEXT>
