<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE manufacturers such as Nissan, the automotive maker, Kobe Steel and
Kawasaki Steel, are increasing fund procurement through US securitisation
agencies.
With the current stock market slump preventing fund-raising through equity,
companies are keen to pursue alternative measures. They are also under
increasing pressure to collect receivable credits, as the slowing economy is
affecting cash flow.
Securitisation of sales credits is restrained in the domestic financial
markets, as securitisation agencies are not permitted. The Securities and
Exchange Act, the Japanese version of the US Glass Steagall Act, also
defines repackaged assets as certificates, preventing the instruments from
being traded as securities.
