<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / International Company News: American HDTV rivals agree to
share royalties
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN groups offering competing technologies to establish a US standard
for high definition television (HDTV) have agreed in principal to share
royalties from the licensing of their technologies if one of them wins
approval from the Federal Communications Commission.
The FCC is currently testing four all-digital HDTV systems. Two are offered
by General Instruments, in collaboration with the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. A third has been proposed by AT&amp;T working with Zenith
Electronics.
In a move to 'share risks and rewards,' the American joint ventures have
agreed that if one of their three systems is adopted they will share
royalties. In addition, the two groups have agreed to work together to
enhance the system selected as a standard by the FCC if necessary. This
might be appropriate, for example, if the FCC testers find a combination of
some aspects of two different systems preferable.
For the time being, however, the two groups will continue to seek adoption
of their respective HDTV systems. The FCC testing is expected to be
completed later this year, with an FCC advisory committee scheduled to make
its recommendation early in 1993 and its final selection in mid-1993.
Mr Richard Wiley, chairman of the FCC advisory committee on advanced
television responsible for conducting the HDTV tests, said that the
agreement is a 'positive development that will help us to achieve our
ultimate goal of the best possible standard'. However, he said that the
agreement will not affect the committee's decision or disadvantage other
entrants.
Also competing in the standard setting tests is an international consortium
led by Philips of the Netherlands and Thomson of France, together with NBC,
a unit of General Electric and the David Sarnoff Research Center in the US.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
