<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 92 / International Company News: Equitable demutualisation moves
closer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Equitable Life Assurance Society, the fourth largest insurance company
in the US, moved a step closer to successful demutualisation yesterday when
policyholders approved the transaction.
Demutualisation is the process whereby a mutual insurer, essentially
controlled by policyholders, turns itself into a 'conventional'
shareholder-owned company. Equitable is the largest US insurer to have taken
this route, but  - given that the need to raise new capital is fairly
widespread in the insurance sector  - others may follow suit.
Equitable's policyholders were asked to vote on the matter on Wednesday.
Some 888,338 policyholders returned ballot cards  - out of a maximum of 2.2m
 - of which 819,964 were in favour. This 92.3 per cent vote in favour easily
surpasses the minimum two-thirds majority needed.
Equitable now needs the go-ahead from the New York State Insurance
Department, which is overseeing the process, and a sale of shares to
investors should proceed this summer. The demutualisation process is of
intense interest to Axa, the large French insurer; it stands to receive up
to 49 per cent of Equitable's equity in return for a Dollars 1bn capital
infusion last year, assuming all goes smoothly.
</TEXT>
